links.slidetitle: Coaching is Like a Good Conversation

slidetranscripts.Text:
Welcome to the StepUP module on Powerful Questions and Active Listening. Likely, you have heard these terms before. Perhaps, though, you are unfamiliar with what they mean in the context of Step UP. This presentation will clarify the meaning and use of these terms as essential coaching tools and share some strategies for you to strengthen your own questioning and listening skills.

Youll navigate through this presentation by clicking the next button in the lower right-hand corner of the screen.

You can also choose specific topics to look at or review by clicking on them in the list of the table of contents on the left.

If youd like to mute the presentation at any time, click the audio speaker in the left-hand corner of the screen.

Click next to continue.

Lets take a look at the objectives for this presentation. Click each box to view the associated objective.

1. How to distinguish between weak and powerful questions.

2. The value of using powerful questions as a coaching tool.

3. The characteristics of active listening.

A Step UP coaching session is like a conversation, and as you know from your own experience, the best conversations happen when there is genuine interest between the two participants. When you are in a good conversation, you are not thinking about what questions you will ask; you are not concerned with right or wrong responses. Instead, you listen closely, without judging, and ask questions to help clarify and discover new insights. Thats exactly what it means to ask powerful questions, your most important coaching tool.

Powerful questions help students think deeply and discover their own answers, solutions and ideas. They are open-ended and require an extended response. In other words, a question that can be answered in a couple of words is not a powerful question. Powerful questions help move the conversation forward. The good news for you is that students do most of the talking; your job is to ask good, non-judgmental questions and then listen closely to the responses.

There are several different types of questions coaches ask students. These include dead-end questions, judgmental questions, and powerful questions. Click on each question mark to the left to learn about each type of question.

Dead-End Questions

These questions invite short, superficial

responses and often begin with:

When

Where

Who

Do you

Did you

Have you

Are you

Try to avoid asking this type of question.

Judgmental Questions

These questions force responders
to defend themselves and often

begin with:

Why

Try to avoid asking judgmental questions.

Powerful Questions

These questions invite students to
think, elaborate and explore their own

ideas and often begin with:

What

How

You should strive to ask your students powerful questions as much as possible.

Try to identify the powerful question!

Powerful questions will lead to an extended, thoughtful response.

Dead-end questions will lead to short, superficial responses.

Looking at the two questions below, determine which is the powerful question.

Select your answer, then click Submit.

Look at the two questions below and determine which is the powerful question.

Select your answer, then click Submit.

Asking powerful questions takes some practice but there are some tips that might make it easier. Click on each student below to hear a tip on asking powerful questions.

Silence is good! Get comfortable with silence. When you ask me a thoughtful question, I need some time to think before I respond. Give me some time and wait for me to reply. I will, I promise!

You dont need to know all the answers. Sometimes all I need is someone to listen and give me a little feedback now and then. I came to you to be a coach, not my professor. I dont need another lecture. I need you to guide me into discovering my own answers. Its much more meaningful to me when I can solve my own problems.

Let me do the talking. If youre doing most of the talking, you might want to re-examine your questions. I want you to listen to me so let me do the heavy lifting. I need you to ask the right questions and then listen to my responses.

Now lets try a scenario.

A student explains to her coach that she is working 40 hours a week and is concerned about failing her classes.

Help the coach decide what to say to the student.

Click the Start button to begin.

After you ask powerful questions, your next important job is to listen carefully to the response.

This also may be a new skill that sounds easy and logical. However, sometimes instead of listening to students, coaches are thinking of what question to ask next.

Instead, trust that the next question will come to you in the moment. Give your students your undivided attention, and be careful not to judge, no matter what the student says. This includes silent responses like a change in body language or expression. Powerful questions sometimes lead to surprising responses. Embrace whatever comes up.

There are several active listening techniques to use as you coach. Click on each part of the ear to view the techniques.

One good strategy is to summarize what you have heard the student say. In that way, the student knows youve been listening carefully and have a good understanding of the situation.

Ask the student some clarifying questions to help you get a clear picture and help the student think more deeply.

Invite the student to elaborate on their response. This gives the student another chance to reflect and give you more details about their situation

One technique is to use body language that says you are 100% engaged in the conversation. You can do that by maintaining eye contact, by sitting up and leaning towards the student. That shows you are paying close attention.

You are now going to watch a short video of a coaching session where the coach uses several of the techniques weve talked about so far.

You will then watch 3 clips of this video and be asked to identify which techniques the coach uses, so pay careful attention to the powerful questions and how carefully and actively the coach listens to the students responses.

Click the play button to begin watching the video.

When youre finished, click the next button to continue to the next slide.

Hopefully this presentation has given you a taste for powerful questions and active listening. Lots more information is available, and this is not the only introduction you will receive. You will get more help and practice in the Step UP workshops. A list of powerful questions is in your manual, and there is more information available on the Step UP Canvas site as well as many You Tube videos online. In addition, you can borrow books, articles and videos about coaching from the Step UP office.

You are a busy person with lots of demands on your time. Thank you for sharing some of that time to learn about powerful questions and active listening, and most importantly, thank you for being a Step UP coach.
